In article <31aaa9$7a0@crl4.crl.com>, Wayne Hoxsie <hoxsiew@crl.com> wrote:
>William Rowe (browe@netcom.com) wrote:
>
>	Just out of curiosity, how many possible CRC values are there for 
>a given number of bytes in a plaintext.  Suppose you used a CRC 32 
>function as a one-way hash for a key phrase, ...

Then you would have no more than 32 bits of information available,
and possibly much less (e.g., if its a small file containing ASCII
encoded English.)

>then used that 32 bit value as a seed for [any pseudo-] random number 
>generator to generate a key as long as the plaintext.  Any estimate on 
>the number of possible keys? 

You could have no more than 32 bits of random key, although you
could smear those bits across a couple hundred bits if you want. :-)

